In the pursuit of an education in social work, I intend to tread a path that leads me to the Division of Family and Children Services, where I shall endeavor to lend aid to those children who have been afflicted by the scourge of abuse and neglect, and to offer support to those families beset by discord. The values that I bring to this endeavor are not mere abstractions but the very essence of my being: service, respect, and a steadfast commitment to the ethical pursuit of improvement in human relationships and my own professional competency. These are not merely the values of a social worker but the cornerstone of my own existence.

I have always been a man possessed of a desire to alleviate the suffering of others, yet the path to this end was obscured by the fog of uncertainty. Throughout my sojourn through high school and college, I have beheld many a soul retreating from their plight in the mire of denial, and a few who have succumbed to false securities. It was this tableau of despair that prompted me to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology, yet the path to a career remained elusive. Thus, I took a respite upon graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One sultry summer's day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old lad, his demeanor as anxious as his circumstances. He sought refuge from an abusive home, and I could not turn away from his plight. The next day, I found myself at his parent's doorstep, a stranger bearing a degree in Psychology. The police were powerless, and so I engaged the parents in a conversation that revealed their hearts to be as beaten and bruised as their son's. This encounter seeded the seed of a career in social work, a means to tend to the wounds of family strife.

Social justice is a value that resonates deeply within me, for our society holds the individual in high esteem, yet we are bound by the chains of conformity. If we mourn the loss of an individual, why do we strive to be like everyone else? I am an individual, and I will not be shackled by the expectations of others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I have protested against the injustices that bind us, coloring my hair with the bold hues of defiance, donning attire that reflects my true self, piercing my ears with the rebellion of my spirit, and declaring my alliance with the Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance. I have fought against racism and discrimination, for I believe in the sanctity of the individual and the justice that is their due. I will continue to stand against the injustices that plague our society, for I am an individual, and I will not be silenced.

The following compendium traverses the labyrinthine terrain of Biological and Sociocultural models in the context of insomnia. The Biological model, like a grim sentinel, stands watch over the inheritance of genetic information and the physiological aspects of health. In stark contrast, the Sociocultural model casts its gaze upon environmental relationships, their reach extending to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia is a sojourn through these models, each step illuminated by the research chosen to illuminate them, and each finding subjected to a critical eye.

Sleep disorders, in their myriad forms, can be characterized as primary, related to another mental disorder, or connected to other issues. The primary sleep disorders, such as Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, stand as the first line of defense against the encroaching darkness of sleeplessness. Those related to mental disorders are but shadows cast by Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other categories of sleep disorders, like ghosts in the night, are born of medical complications or the specter of substance intake. Dyssomnias, with their focus on initiation and maintenance of sleep, include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). In the realm of Parasomnias, the nightmares and terrors that beset the sleeping are the haunting echoes of behavioral abnormalities and physiological occurrences.

The biological model of sleep disorders, a grim litany of genes and heritable factors, delves into the physiologically acquired aspects. In the deep, dark chasm of the hypothalamus, neurons containing orexin regulate the dance of sleep and wakefulness. A study of mice, in the language of science, revealed the presence of phenotypic GABAB receptors on these orexin neurons, responsible for the states of sleep and wakefulness. The activation of the GABAA receptor, like a soothing lullaby, brings forth sleep. Inhibition of this receptor, as if the silence of a haunted house, reduces anxiety and induces sleep. The application of a GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time, a beacon of hope in the darkness (Matsuki et al., 2009). This study, like a map to the promised land, implies that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This suggests a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A defect or absence in this receptor could hinder the ability to sleep unaided by medication. The sociocultural implications, like the echo of a gunshot in the night, suggest that if this phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep. An alteration of the receptor, a glitch in the matrix, would disturb sleep, casting a shadow over the individual's life, tainting their days with the monotony of sleeplessness and the struggle to focus.

The travail of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) unfolds in realms beyond mere audibility. It is not an affliction of the ears, but a malady of the mind, a fracture in the central nervous system's ability to harness and decipher auditory information. The brain, that labyrinthine organ, fails in its duty to translate sound into meaning, leaving those stricken with CAPD to grapple with a world that echoes without substance.

The origins of this condition can be traced back to the mid-20th century, when researchers first began to unravel the mysteries of "auditory imperception." The path of discovery was marked by the pioneering efforts of researchers like Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, who in 1954 began to develop tests for children with communicative disorders, and later, by Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing and his model of the physiological activity underlying auditory perception in 1961. A gathering of luminaries in 1977 further fueled the fires of research into CAPD.

Manifestations of the disorder vary in their cruelty. The afflicted may find it impossible to pinpoint the source of a sound, or to differentiate between acoustic events. They may struggle to recognize patterns in sound, to parse the subtle shifts in speech that betray sarcasm, or to decipher the sequence in which auditory information is presented. Some may find their thoughts disrupted by the intrusion of subsequent sounds.

The diagnosis of CAPD is a complex endeavor, requiring the keen eye and skilled hand of audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others. It involves a myriad of tests and measures, from questionnaires and observations to advanced recordings of acoustic signals within the ear. Yet, despite these efforts, a single tool of diagnostic certainty remains elusive, and the root cause of CAPD remains shrouded in mystery.

The play "Twelfth Night" seems to imply that, whilst disguise may prove expedient in the art of long deception, it is ultimately a double-edged blade. For, in the inevitable unmasking, a person risks losing their true self. Such a predicament presents a conundrum: the choice between self-preservation and the preservation of relationships, for some may bear the deception with neutrality, whilst others will be offended and seek retribution.

The theme of deception in gender role reversal is particularly thorny, for it raises questions of identity and purpose. Why, then, does a person feel the need to shed their true form and don the guise of the opposite sex? In Viola's case, it is clear: a means of self-preservation. With her arrival in a strange land, she conceals her true self to evade potential harm. Her plan succeeds, yet it also isolates her from women, severing a vital support. Worse still, her deception entangles her in romantic complications. Olivia, mistaking her for Sebastian, falls in love with Cesario, and Orsino's suppressed affections for Viola surface.

This, perhaps, is a progressive stance, but to the modern observer, "Twelfth Night" may be seen as a tale of how deception can unveil hidden emotions. Consider Olivia and Orsino's unexpressed desires, possibly stirred by the presence of Viola/Cesario. Is Olivia's love for Cesario rooted in her attraction to men, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? This is a question worth pondering, for Olivia's character seems to embody the shallow judgments of her time. This is evident in her swift changes of heart, from loving Cesario to regarding Viola as a sister.

German colonial rule, in its harshness, is often remembered for the atrocities committed against the Ovaherero and Nama of South West Africa. Yet, the empire's broad sweep cannot be accounted for by a single brushstroke. The colonial machine was as varied as the terrain it sought to subjugate. Educational provisions across the colonies mirrored this diversity. When the British assumed control of German East Africa in 1919, they found a populace that was, for the most part, educated and literate. Similarly, German efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were commended by contemporary observers. Yet, South West Africa (what is now Namibia) presented a stark contrast. Unlike in East Africa, where the government actively engaged in the education of natives, here the task was largely left to missionary societies, receiving scant support from the government. Instead, the colonial state poured resources into educating Europeans, establishing schools and regulating missionary endeavors. These policies left a lasting impact on South West Africa, even after the Germans were gone. While other colonies boasted literate African populations, South West Africa remained largely untouched, uneducated, and illiterate. Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this divergent experience. This paper intends to delve deeper, identifying these factors and focusing on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards the native Africans.
A plethora of literature exists on education under German colonial rule, much of it written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the colonial period. These early works primarily aimed to describe the educational systems of the colonies. Later works, in English, expanded upon this discourse, comparing educational systems across the colonies and offering more detailed analyses. These studies highlighted significant variations. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa stands out, comparing the two colonies and discussing the factors that accounted for their differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa was a key factor in shaping its educational system.
South West Africa possessed a climate that was moderately temperate, though much of the territory was covered by arid desert. The European population reflected this relative hospitability. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, compared to only 5,336 in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The categorization of Popular Music has expanded over the past century, encompassing a multitude of genres, each with its own labyrinth of sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. To name a few, there's rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, each a realm unto itself. Among these, Heavy Metal rock, a genre birthed four decades past, stands as one of the most variegated and expressive. It is expressive, for it embraces a spectrum of emotions, albeit largely those that tread the darker path. It is diverse, too, as early pioneers recognized its adaptability, giving rise to an ever-branching tapestry of sub-genres.

Today, the heavy metal movement has evolved into a vast, almost unfathomable, collection of niches. It has absorbed themes from other genres, yet its roots run deep. To comprehend the metal music that permeates our world today, one must first grasp the essence of the metal movement, and why it transcends mere genre classification.

Metal, in many ways, is a movement defined by its embrace of darkness. It is a music of extremes - more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less simplicity, more virtuosity; metal musicians are true artisans, their skill evident in every note. It is also a movement with a heavy influence of psychedelic drugs. The mid-70s' drug boom led to a wave of 'crazy' records, the music an outlet for the artists' otherworldly experiences. It possesses a raw, visceral quality, a stark contrast to much of the music of the time, which often shied away from the darker spectrum of emotion. Later generations have drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral qualities of the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as these from Helter Skelter, by the Beatles, exhibit this darkness. Often cited as one of the first Heavy Metal songs, it was a response to a Rolling Stones track, an attempt to match their heavier, darker sound. The Beatles, it seems, were eager to prove they could be just as heavy as the Stones.

In the waning years of the nineteenth century, long before the Surrealists began to whisk their dreams onto canvas, a man named Henri Rousseau was weaving his own visions into his art. The Dream, a painting from 1910, is not merely a depiction of a woman captivated by a dreamt landscape, but a mirror to Rousseau's own aspirations and the turmoil that swirled within him. He yearned for acceptance, for praise, for a place among the esteemed artists he revered. Yet, he found himself at a crossroads, torn between the path of conformity and the lure of his own unique voice.

To truly understand The Dream, one must first delve into the life of this self-taught painter. Born in the bleak town of Laval, France, on May 21, 1844, Rousseau hailed from humble beginnings, his father a tinsmith and hardware dealer. Formal art training eluded him, but he found his way into the world of art through his work as a gabelou, later living with the moniker douanier, a customs inspector. The death of his wife and eight children added to his burden, and he sought solace in painting, yearning for a new life.

Rousseau's desire for acceptance was not misplaced. He was late to the art world, uneducated in the intricacies of painting, and faced the daunting task of making his mark amidst a sea of talented contemporaries. It was only when his career was well underway that recognition began to surface, around the same time that Henri Matisse was making his name. Yet, there was a stark difference between these two painters, as noted by Jan Gordon in Modern French Painters. Matisse sought to avoid clichés, while Rousseau yearned for the conventional, hoping that his work, so ordinary, would gain him entry into the esteemed circle of the Artiste Français.

In the shadowed corners of knowledge, many a sage has whispered of a union between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I hold that this nexus is not merely a coincidence, but a symbiosis as ancient as the earth itself. As Keats intones in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of life's wisdom is imparted through the schoolmaster's tongue or the fractious road, yet we find ourselves drawn to the ethical and the aesthetically pleasing without being led by these guides. Both ethics and aesthetics are but attempts to unravel the tapestry of existence, rather than to prescribe the colors on the loom. Our musings on morality and beauty are chiefly exercises in explication, not dictate.

More often than not, the critical eye fails to grasp the very essence of the good or the beautiful. A discourse on the Mona Lisa's worth may dwell upon such minutiae as fore and afterground, contrast's dance, or cultural context's sway, but in the end, these are but shadows cast by the masterpiece's light. True appreciation, it seems, begins with a whisper — "There's just something..." — before the more complex or critical explanation takes flight. Both art and morality, I believe, elude complete description. As O'Connor reminds us, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way...you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how meticulously we catalog a tome's properties, there remains a whisper of the ineffable. So too with morality.

I postulate that the moral and the artistic are so intertwined because they strike us at a level both experienced and inexplicable, a realm that Kant would call noumenal. Their kinship is strongest in the art of literature. As McKean observes, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

In the resplendent heart of today's Germany, a coalescence of cultures unfurls, from the alpine shadows of München to the Baltic's embrace in Kiel. This tapestry, woven with threads of myriad hues, is felt from Köln by the Rhine, through the country's very soul, to the Saxon city of Dresden, whose Elbe river carves its path. Such an amalgamation of culture should not be a surprise, for Germany's formative years were shaped by the fusion of disparate sources and tribes.

Germania, the cradle of the German people, bears a name shrouded in mystery. Its origin is a matter of scholarly debate. Tacitus, in his work "Germania," written in 98 AD, proposes that the name emerged from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who had previously been christened "Germani." Others suggest the name derives from the Latin word "germanus," used by Julius Caesar to distinguish between those he conquered, the Gauls, and those he did not, the Germanic tribes. Still others posit that the name may have come from the Old Irish "garim," meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans' boisterous nature. Whatever the origin, the name has stuck, a testament to the enduring power of language.

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et Situ Germanorum," penned, "I should regard the Germans as aboriginal, and not mixed with other races. For, in former times, it was not by land but by sea that those who sought to emigrate would arrive." The Romans, too, were drawn to Germania, not for its warmth or grandeur, but for its goods and the skill of its warriors within their ranks. Thus, the Germanic tribes, appearing in the first century, found themselves living on the empire's borders, trading their wares and serving in the Roman legions.

Downward my gaze fell, the tableau before me unspooling like a scroll, blank save for the stark lines of reality. Unlabeled, unvarnished, the scene took shape in my consciousness, a landscape of stark simplicity, a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen, a kitchen in a dining room, all reduced to mere lines and shapes by the unforgiving eye of my mind. Thoughts danced like spiders, weaving and unraveling in the quietude of my thoughts, each one a fleeting visitor, not quite leaving its mark. It was a dance of perception, a ballet of observation, and I was but the spectator, the silent witness to the world laid bare.

Born with a pencil in hand, I had long yearned to capture the world in lines and color, to wield the tool of creation. The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain, a tome of wisdom bestowed upon me by an artist I once knew, had become my guide, a roadmap to the labyrinth of the mind where the pencil meets the canvas. It taught me to frame the world, to reduce the complexity of a scene to its most essential parts, to see the simple shape within the chaos.

In that moment, the bowl of fruit, the kitchen, the dining room, they were more than just a scene; they were a canvas, a landscape waiting for the brush of my perception. I was a painter, a sculptor, a creator, and before me lay the first brushstroke, the first line in my story, Work in Brown.

My fingers touched the handle of my chosen implement, a toilet brush, and the world shifted. The smooth water, the swirling vortex, it all became a canvas, a stage for the dance of my hand. I was the puppeteer, and the brush was my marionette, jerking and spasming, dancing in the rhythm of my will. The offending brown package, a testament to the folly of humanity, refused to yield, entrenched as a slug in the depths of the bowl.

The mop, a loose grip, a stance wide and steady, the green tie knotted against the collar of my shirt, all bore witness to my struggle. The rude bundle of processed matter, a message left for those who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid, was more than just a nuisance. It was a challenge, a test of my resolve, a reminder of the world's imperfections.

My hand moved, a slow descent, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey, a delicate dance with the abyss. And in that moment, I was not just a cleaner; I was an artist, a creator, a scribe of the world's imperfections.

In the grim crucible of youth, young souls are claimed by the steel and asphalt, their lives snuffed out in the blink of an eye. The National Institutes of Health, in their unyielding pursuit of truth, have illuminated one aspect of this grim dance with death: the teen brain, in its formative state, is not yet equipped to navigate the perils of the open road. This naivety, this innocence, is as much a curse as it is a blessing. It is inexperience that lies at the heart of this calamity, a blindfolded child stumbling into a world of steel and speed.

The company of peers, a poisoned chalice, amplifies their folly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has charted a grim correlation: more passengers, more accidents. California and other states have responded with provisional licenses, a Band-Aid on a bleeding wound. But these measures are but a temporary salve, for the truth is stark and unyielding: the youngest drivers, in their entirety, are not yet ready to bear the weight of responsibility.

Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman, in his cold, clinical gaze, has peered into the abyss and seen a desire for risk that burns bright and fierce. The thrill-seekers, they are called, these children of the digital age, and they are a plague upon the highways. It is wisdom, not folly, that would delay their descent into the crucible of the open road until the fever of youth has begun to subside.

By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, a fresh wave of inexperienced drivers ready to plunge into the maelstrom. Legislation, it is whispered, could stem this tide. Driver's education in schools, the first steps on the path to wisdom, but no young soul under the age of eighteen should wield the keys to a motor vehicle. A provisional permit, a trial by fire, and a certain number of hours behind the wheel, the number determined by the majority of states. A uniform law, a beacon in the storm, guiding these young souls safely through the perils of the open road.

This is not a new idea, a fresh dawn. It is a truth whispered in the shadows, a truth that will not be denied.

In perusing the Library of Congress's archive of Edison's earliest cinematic works, I encountered a clutch of fifteen trick films, dating from 1895 to 1901. These films, like their kin from that era, played with the eye's perceptions, employing creative editing to weave illusions. My study, much like a man unearthing ancient secrets, delved into the poetics of these deceptions, with an eye towards the peculiarities that bloomed in the latter years. The trick films of that time, much like the theatre they mimicked, were rooted in the stationary proscenium, with no camera movement, and adhered to the dictum that one shot equaled one film. Yet, there were renegades among them, daring to spurn these rules, introducing the notion of multiple shots.

One commonality that seeped through these films was their preference for interior sets, framed within a rigid proscenium. The camera, steadfast and unmoving, bore witness to the action that unfolded within its gaze. This, much like the theatre and vaudeville acts that preceded it, dictated the movement of actors, confining them to a horizontal axis. Consider, for instance, the dance of the actors in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900). They entered from the right, moved back and forth, and exited, all without the camera's intervention.

The proscenium style also dictated that shots be long and, less frequently, medium. Close-ups were an anomaly, a stranger in that world. This, too, was a nod to the theatre, where the audience took in the entire performance at once, framed by the borders of the stage. The actors, much like the characters in these films, did not stray from the middle ground, never moving towards or away from the camera's cold eye.

The films, much like the theatre, often followed the rule that one conceptual shot equaled one film, limiting their duration to a minute or less. This also restricted their dramatic or narrative capabilities, most focusing on brief vaudeville-style tricks. Yet, in these films, what the viewer saw as one shot was often a collage of several, the physical shots joined to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance. In "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), a closer look reveals where the physical shot of Mary's "head" begins, though the entire film is perceived as one shot.

John Taylor, hailing from Caroline, was an early and steadfast advocate for the Republican cause. Born an agriculturalist, his life and brief foray into politics forged a man of unwavering dedication and outspoken convictions concerning personal liberties and governance. His deep-rooted belief in an agrarian system underpinned his views on sovereignty, constitutionalism, and even the judicial system.

Taylor saw the young United States as an unparalleled opportunity to craft an ideal society, unencumbered by native traditions that might hinder progress. He revered the natural rights of men, asserting that they were interdependent, and that denying any one would diminish the value of the rest. These rights, he posited, should be beyond the government's grasp. He viewed the "state of nature" as a harsh realm where the strong and cunning prospered, but civilized society must not replicate this brutality.

To achieve this utopia, Taylor believed a government must acknowledge and account for man's inherent good and evil. He held fast to a dualistic morality, claiming, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). Good principles, he posited, protected private property, promoted agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. A government rooted in such principles would function equitably, regardless of administrative avarice and self-interest. While recognizing self-interest as man's primary motivation, he deemed it evil only when it subverted the creation of a society based on the public good.

Taylor, like many of his time, advocated for a strict construction of the Constitution. He yearned for a limited Federal government, with no powers beyond those explicitly stated. He understood that an expansive Federal government could become despotic. Yet, he cautioned against a simple, literal interpretation, as it could easily become corrupt without reference to the writers' intent. He considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, for it more plainly described the nation as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

In reviewing Fig. 17, an abrupt decline in commuter log submissions became apparent in the third month of our project. This sudden drop was a discouraging sight, its cause shrouded in mystery. As winter descended upon our New England campus, fewer took to the roads on bicycle or foot, a natural explanation for some of the fall-off. December, too, brought the end of the fall semester - a time when students and faculty alike were engrossed in frantic preparations for the holidays and the processing of grades. Amidst this turmoil, the commuter log may have slipped from their minds. The holiday season, with its extended break, further diminished the need for campus attendance. Classes resumed in late January, perhaps accounting for the low February submissions. Yet none of this fully explains the February slump. It could be surmised that the project's initial fervor had waned, as such initiatives often do.

To combat this waning enthusiasm, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special blitz aimed at reinvigorating the project. This indeed resulted in an uptick in log submissions. The challenge, however, lay not only in maintaining the project's momentum but also in counteracting the inertia of holiday and semester breaks.

Another obstacle faced was the inherent allure of driving one's car, deeply ingrained in our culture. To encourage alternative commuting modes, we offered prizes - gift certificates to local eateries, an independent bookstore, and even national chain stores. The idea of larger prizes, such as bicycles or hybrid/electric cars, was intriguing but untested. If prizes had been increased gradually, say announcing bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January, participation might have risen rather than dipped.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a form of security that tracks an index, commodity, or basket of assets much like an index fund, yet it trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF offers the diversification of an index fund coupled with the singular ownership benefits of a stock, such as short selling, margin buying, and the purchase of as little as one share. While these advantages are appealing, they come with a trade-off—ETFs typically charge a commission for each trade, akin to stock orders. Moreover, ETFs boast a wide array of funds, but a discerning investor should evaluate whether these stated benefits, like diversification, actually exist and to what extent.

For our examination, we'll focus on the iShares MSCI Emerging Markets ETF (IHF) and compare it to its top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of its total assets. Below are the top 10 holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To gauge how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF, we'll calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return, normalized to 100%. The results are as follows:

From these calculations, it is evident that a portfolio composed solely of the top 10 holdings yields a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 points lower than the ETF's overall Beta. Thus, it appears that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer higher returns with a lower Beta. However, statistical significance between these two portfolios remains to be established.

To determine if these portfolios differ statistically, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks, normalizing it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

In the annals of Edgar Allan Poe's verse, "Dream-Land" stands as one of his most haunting compositions. Within its pages, he employs the term "Thulé," echoing a reference from Virgil, who used it to denote an island beyond the known world, north of Britain. Yet, there exists a more contemporary source that must be acknowledged. Poe, it is known, was deeply engrossed in the works of German authors.

This connection is of great significance, for it reveals Poe's familiarity with the writings of Goethe. Karl J. Arndt, in his meticulous examination of Poe's "Politian" and Goethe's "Mignon," draws a compelling parallel between the two poets' works, concluding that Poe was, indeed, drawing inspiration from Goethe's pen.

Goethe, a luminary in the realm of literary endeavor, penned the tragic verse drama "Faust," which was published in two parts, the first in 1808, and the second in 1832, the year of his passing. Within this latter section lies a short poem titled "The King of Thulé," a tale of a king who, grief-stricken by the death of his queen, succumbs to despair and ultimately meets his end. The parallels between this king and the speaker of Poe's "Dream-Land" are striking, as if Poe himself had stepped into the shadow of Goethe's own words.

Poe's use of Thulé is not confined to "Dream-Land" alone. He references "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," and employs the term twice more as bookends in "Dream-Land." These two poems can be viewed as companion pieces, with "Dream-Land" acting as a vivid exploration of the themes and imagery present in Goethe's "The King of Thulé." The landscape of Thulé, as described by the speaker, is one of darkness, loneliness, and haunting memories of lost friends, a realm devoid of color and life. This description mirrors the despair and desolation felt by the King of Thulé, who, much like the speaker, is haunted by the memory of his deceased queen and the loss of his will to live.

Goethe's influence on Poe is undeniable, and it is likely that Poe, a man of deep literary admiration, would have been exposed to Goethe's works through the many reproductions circulating at the time. His respect for Tennyson, too, would have led him to explore the works of this celebrated German author.

In the vast expanse of California's legal landscape, the question stands as to whether a patron, after succumbing to the treacherous embrace of an applesauce spill in the belly of D&D's groceries, might find solace in the cold, unyielding justice of punitive damages, given the derelict nature of the store's manager. To walk the plank of this legal inquiry, one must first navigate the treacherous waters of malice, a concept that stirs the souls of judges and lawyers alike.

A judge, wise in the ways of the law, would not lightly dismiss such a claim. To prove that punitive damages are justified, a plaintiff must lay bare the defendant's actions, demonstrating a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would befall others. Jennifer Palmer, our plaintiff, will argue that the defendant, Paul Martin, should have known the peril of his inaction, given the silent sentinels of previous slips and falls that had befallen D&D's patrons. Despite this, Martin stood resolute, his dinner break a testament to his indifference.

On the thirteenth of October, at the hour of five, an employee named Rich Wayne reported an applesauce spill to Martin, his words echoing in the void of managerial apathy. Martin, consumed by his own appetites, dismissed the matter with a wave of his hand, leaving the spill to fester like an open wound. Mary J. Haddigan, another employee, did her duty and notified Martin again, but the manager's heart remained unmoved. At the stroke of half-past five, the stage was set for disaster as Jennifer Palmer, our unfortunate patron, slipped and fell, her back a casualty of the ignored peril.

The echoes of these incidents do not stand alone. Five such incidents had already stained the pages of D&D's accident reports in the year that had passed. Yet, Martin, a man of apparent malice, stood by, his conduct a testament to a willful disregard for the safety of his patrons. The law, in its infinite wisdom, has decreed that such conduct, committed with a despicable disregard for the rights and safety of others, is indeed malice.

California's legal tapestry weaves a thread of malice into its fabric, defining it as conduct that intends harm, or, in the absence of intent, conduct that is despicable and committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the safety of others. Courts have characterized such conduct as malicious when the defendant is aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his actions, yet willfully and deliberately fails to avoid those consequences. It is in this light that we must examine the actions of Paul Martin, and the fate that awaits the punitive damage claim of Jennifer Palmer.

Four years past, I encountered a course on the faith of Islam, taught at CBC. The class was a crucible of debate, the chief contention being whether Islam harbors hostility. The pertinence of this inquiry, I now believe, has never been more acute. Since the day of infamy, the mass media's perspective has oscillated wildly, from a hostile view of Islam and its extremists to a state of near-tolerance, a shift that, in 2001, seemed unimaginable. A president like Barack Obama, with a Muslim heritage, would have been inconceivable then.

The Prophet's Biography piqued my interest. The narrative of Muhammad, as presented, seems at odds with the historical record. The Muhammad I've encountered is a figure of force, compelling tribes to adopt Islam through conquest. Yet, the biography paints him as a martyr, misunderstood and meek. It is this disparity that troubles me. The stories of his 'miracles' share uncanny echoes with those of Jesus. The tale of the multiplying mutton and milk echoes the loaves and fishes. This stylistic choice, I find, serves to diminish the miracle of Jesus, as if the life of Muhammad is a pale imitation.

Moreover, the stories in the biography, while claiming to offer witness, often come from third-party accounts. The narrative of hearsay, of 'so-and-so heard from so-and-so,' diminishes the credibility of the tales, casting doubt on their veracity.

What disquiets me most is the attempt to elevate Muhammad, to cast him as a godly man, humble and wise. Yet, history tells a different tale. If today's Muslims were to learn the truth of Muhammad's rise, I wonder how it would inform their faith.

The teachings of the man they call Jesus, and the beliefs he held in his mortal days, were swiftly abandoned as Christianity took root upon the earth. The history of this faith, if viewed with a broad, sweeping gaze, reveals a ceaseless drift from its origins. The present world, it seems, is marked by an ever-increasing consciousness and a unprecedentedly progressive spirit. Though traditionalists persist, their influence may yet prove insufficient to sway the whole. Among those who claim the name of Christ, a deepening understanding of history will spread, a yearning to distinguish the doctrines added over time from the true intent of their founder. This reversal is as inevitable as the setting of the sun, a process that will strip away the layers of belief, one by one, like the hands of time ticking backwards, until only the essence of what Jesus brought to the world remains. When this tide of change sweeps across the United States and Europe, it will carry with it a multitude, leading them to worship as if they themselves walked in the time of Jesus, guided by his words alone. The church, in its institutional might, will stand strong, yet the theological clock will have turned back, and the profusion of diversity within Christendom will give way to a uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, between sects, between every division, differences will fade away, revealing a singular truth. Human history is rife with such reversals. Once reviled and persecuted, Christianity became the state religion of Rome. The tables have turned since the dark days of African-American slavery, and the tables will turn again in the arena of the Christian faith, seeking the source and undoing the diversity in its wake. But this process will be made possible by a new way of reading Jesus' words, not as literal edicts, but as metaphorical parables. What, then, has transpired since the days of Jesus?

If we delve far enough into the annals of history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning of the Christian faith. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at its core, by the time Rome had seized Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people were not united in spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the common folk.

In the grim heart of man, there lies a dark current, an insatiable hunger for gain and power, a selfishness that knows no bounds. This is the truth Upton Sinclair laid bare in his grim tale, "The Jungle." The factory owners and managers, those men with eyes like coal and hearts as cold as the river's flow, saw only their own ambition, their own empire to forge. They cared not for the smoke that choked the lungs of children nor the stench of animal waste that fouled the earth. The very air was rent with the ceaseless din of their industry, a symphony of greed and neglect.

These leviathans of progress cared not for the men who toiled in their service. "From the top to the bottom, it was a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds," Sinclair wrote. The men were but cogs in a beastly machine, their lives had no value save in their ability to produce wealth. They were forced to labor in brutal conditions, their bodies and spirits broken by the relentless pace. A sudden layoff, a gleam in the eye of a manager, and multitudes were cast aside like so much refuse. There were no laws to shield these poor souls, no organizations to champion their cause. The unions, they were little more than wolves in sheep's clothing, fleecing the flock they were meant to protect.

These men, these slaves of the machine, were trapped in a system as unforgiving as the wilderness, as harsh as the winter's frost. They were expected to endure the hell of Packingtown, to accept their fate as a matter of course. There was no escape, no respite, only the endless cycle of toil and despair. Sinclair's words echo with the pitiful cry of a people crushed under the heel of progress: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation, dependent for their opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers."

In the vast expanse of narrative waters, authors chart diverse courses to evoke sentiments and attitudes toward pivotal subjects. Fitzgerald, with his pen, navigates these waters deftly in "The Great Gatsby." His techniques, both subtle and profound, weave a tapestry that enthralls the reader.

He pairs nouns and adjectives in ways that dance on the edge of convention, conferring upon the reader a sense of the ethereal. Symbols, too, are his tools, imbued with meaning and wielded to evoke emotions. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald bathes his narrative in hues, each one a whisper of significance: gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink.

White and gray, his steadfast companions, carry the weight of uniformity. White, a beacon of elegance and refinement, and gray, a whisper of decay and age. Fitzgerald introduces these hues in the novel's opening, a symphony of white: Daisy and Jordan, constant in their pristine attire, and Nick, donning "white flannels" at Gatsby's party. Even the uninvited Tom wears a "white shirt" in his tryst with Myrtle. The city itself is a canvas, with Nick descending into "white chasms of lower New York" and the "gray names" of partygoers etched on his mind. Even the mundane is infused with these hues: Jordan and Daisy's shared "white girlhood," the "gray land" of ashes, the "gray" Italian child, and the "gray old man" of the dog-seller.

After having woven a tale of significance around these hues, Fitzgerald applies them to Daisy, the elusive object of Gatsby's longing. When she emerges in her "little white roadster," she becomes a fixture, a uniform addition to the tapestry of the story. The "gray haze" of her fur collar, and her "white" dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter, serve to diminish her character, reducing her to a symbol of Gatsby's desire.

Fitzgerald's use of color is a masterful dance, a ballet of emotions and significations. He turns the mundane into the profound, the ordinary into the extraordinary, all through the delicate art of imbuing color with meaning.

In the sun-scorched lands of San Diego County, the earth yields bountifully, fed by a benevolent climate that caresses the land in warm embrace. Tomatoes, lemons, and other fruits of the earth swell and ripen under the golden sun, while the earth is nurtured by the hands of those who till her soil. The soil, rich and unspoiled, bears witness to the toil of farmers who tend to it with care, for it is the lifeblood of their existence. This is a land where the line between nature and the human spirit blurs, where the organic certification is a badge of honor, a testament to the respect for the land and its inhabitants.

The market for such pure, unadulterated produce is robust, with a hunger for the untouched taste of nature's bounty. The demand for organic eggs and milk is insatiable, their consumers craving the simplicity of true sustenance. The landowner, a visionary, sees the potential in this untapped market, a niche where the scales of nature and commerce intersect. Yet, the path to this promised land is fraught with challenges, for the organic farm demands more from its keeper than the conventional fields. It requires a constant vigilance, a ceaseless battle against pest and weed, a delicate dance with the soil to nurture its life and yield its fruits.

The land in question lies in the shadow of the grand Cleveland National Forest, a parcel of 160 acres that bears the marks of the past. It is a landscape that has known the touch of the Native American hand and the boot of the cattle rancher, a testament to the enduring spirit of the land. It stands in the heart of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, a sanctuary home to a hundred species, many of them endangered, their existence teetering on the precipice of oblivion.

The ecoregion's conservation plan is still being debated, but the fate of these creatures hangs in the balance. The Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, and the California gnatcatcher all call this land home, their survival intertwined with the health of the land. The landowner, a beacon of hope, seeks to be both a conserver and a creator, a guardian of the past and a visionary of the future. He seeks guidance, a path to balance the scales of profit and preservation, a way to turn the tide for the creatures that call this land home.

Culture, an elusive beast, is both what it is and what it is not. It is not a static thing, nor is it singular. It is a tapestry woven with threads of history, prejudice, and personal experience. To presume that all Russians are stubborn or all Japanese are accommodating is to oversimplify the complex dance of culture. A negotiator would do well to understand the spirit of a culture, its rhythm, and how it will shape the parley.

When one steps into the arena of a foreign culture, one does not see only what is present, but also what is absent. One must accept, without judgment, the culture's quirks and idiosyncrasies, for these are the bones of its meaning. Respect for tradition and belief, even in the heart of a stranger's land, can ease the negotiation's passage.

Culture does not confine itself to national borders. Within each nation, companies carve out their own worlds, with unique languages, customs, and beliefs. It is in the dress codes, the manner of speech, the way duties are delegated, and the charities they endorse that one can glimpse a company's culture. Even within the vast expanse of the American corporate landscape, there is diversity, from the relentless to the laissez-faire, from the urban to the suburban.

Values, the heart of a culture, provide its purpose. If face or harmony are valued, a negotiator will not dishonor them. Likewise, if a hard bargain is prized, the urge to settle will be tempered. Before the negotiation, it is wise to understand these values. Yet, to know one's opponent on a personal level can bring a subtle, yet powerful, edge to the parley.

"The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" Thus begins Psalm 14, and so does St. Anselm's argument for the existence of God. This sentiment is echoed by another thinker we shall discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Both, so it seems, believe in the same deity, the God of the Bible. To fairly weigh their arguments, we must start with the presumption that both are correct in their belief.

To sway from this path would be to lose the essence of their arguments, for they each defend a singular God. However, both arguments, despite their merits, fail to provide a comprehensive basis for belief.

St. Anselm's argument, in its bare bones, posits that God's existence can be found within our own understanding. He suggests that we need not venture beyond our souls to find evidence of Him, but rather to look within. This idea, though convoluted in its articulation, implies that God's existence is self-evident within our own minds. This notion is akin to the Christian concept of faith, wherein acceptance is required in the absence of irrefutable evidence.

St. Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, argues that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without the need for faith. This approach, one might argue, is advantageous for evangelism, as it allows for the recruitment of converts based on logic alone. He presents five logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument essentially posits that the necessity of God can be logically deduced from the world around us.

In the shadows of a distant era, circa the fifth or sixth century before the Common Era, a prince was born, who would one day be known as the Buddha. Over the expanse of his life, he turned his back on the world, attaining enlightenment, and his teachings birthed Buddhism, the most steadfast branch of which is Theravada Buddhism. This religion, now some twenty-five hundred years old, bears little resemblance to its origins, as evidenced by the annual water-cutting ceremony in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka. Monks and laymen alike partake in this ritual, though the Buddha himself never spoke of such festivities. These deviations stretch from superficial traditions to the very heart of the religion's soteriological core. The Theravada Buddhist community, from the cloister to the hearth, has had to alter its doctrinal tenets over the centuries, driven by forces both internal and external, hostile and benign.

To navigate this discussion, we must understand several qualifying terms. Internal forces are those born within the fold of the Buddhasasana, regardless of their status. External forces originate from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that seek to harm or damage the Buddhist community, driven by a malicious perception of Buddhism. Benign forces, while not necessarily seeking to help or hinder, may inadvertently do so.

First, let us delve into the essentials of the religion—the doctrines that form the bedrock of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma, the essence of doctrine, is composed of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of sacred texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka holds the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka comprises the metaphysical components. These include Anatta, the absence of a fixed soul; Dukkha, the inherent suffering of life; and Anicca, the impermanence of all things. Recognizing these concepts allows one to break free of Sansara, the cycle of birth and rebirth, and thereby end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, and achieve enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for life, five for laymen (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not indulge in intoxicating substances), and many more for monks. The most fundamental doctrinal notion is the four noble truths: First, the truth of suffering, Dukkha; second, the truth that attachment causes suffering; third, the truth that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico, once bound in a protracted rivalry that spanned fifty-seven years, from 1836 to 1893, bear witness to a feud that has echoed through history. The zenith of this enmity was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States, with a swift and decisive blow, vanquished Mexico and laid claim to Texas and the American Southwest, new fields for the hungry nation. The tension did not dissipate with this single conflict; it simmered, a boil beneath the surface, until the Great War put an end to it (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The root of this animosity was as much about material interests as it was about differing beliefs, a clash of cultures and traditions, a rift between the Protestant and the Catholic (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This is not an anomaly, but a common tale told among nations that share a border, their interests intertwined in a dance of power and aspiration. The United States and Mexico are but two among many pairs of neighboring nations, bound by proximity and adversity. David M. Pletcher (1977) posits, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, these two nations, geographically close to the United States, have been entangled in a web of rivalry, while others in Latin America have enjoyed a more amicable relationship.

Religious differences, a familiar foe to many a nation, have strained the bond between the United States and Mexico. Sally Frahm (2001) asserts, "If in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth, they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). The ideological struggle between the United States and Mexico was not merely a contest of political ideologies, but a clash of religious persuasions. This enmity was a relic of the historic distrust between the English and Spanish, a legacy that impeded the establishment of cordial diplomatic relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) enumerate seventeen disputes between Mexico and the United States during this fifty-seven-year period. Most of these disputes were territorial in nature, born of raids from Mexican territory into American soil and other frontier problems (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). The border was a frontier, a wild and unpredictable place, where outlaws and bandits operated with impunity, their raids a constant threat until both nations exerted military force to tame the wildlands.

Schmitt (1974) attests that the rivalry began to abate as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the United States, a shift that culminated in American ambitions moving from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico, marking the end of an era in the late 19th century (p. 109-110).

Fifteen‭ ‬years passed since the illness, uninvited and unforeseen,‭ ‬seized me with an iron grip,‭ ‬rendering me unable to tend to the bodies I‭'d‭ ‬once cared for as a nurse. I was a‭ ‬child of uncertainty,‭ ‬and the voice of certainty in my life was the whispered promise‭: "You'll always find work, people will always need tending." So,‭ ‬despite my heart yearning for the lab or the newsroom,‭ ‬I found solace in the steady rhythm of the sickroom. At forty-six,‭ ‬single,‭ ‬and destitute,‭ ‬I am now a stranger to my own body and my life a relentless,‭ ‬daily struggle. My Social Security Disability has seen to it that I am not starving,‭ ‬but the pride and security of self-sufficiency have long since fled. I am a man adrift,‭ ‬but not alone in my tumultuous sea. My family and a few steadfast friends have been my anchor,‭ ‬their kindness my only certainty in this storm.

The truth remains,‭ ‬life is a tapestry of emergencies,‭ ‬both large and small,‭ ‬and no amount of preparation can shield from the unexpected. I agree,‭ ‬the government is a decrepit,‭ ‬rotting beast,‭ ‬but I see no need to abandon it entirely.‭ ‬Instead,‭ ‬I long for a nation of mutual respect,‭ ‬one that trusts in the strength of community. The rugged individualism that once defined us‭ ‬was not the force that carried us through,‭ ‬but compassion and unity. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not do so alone,‭ ‬but as a united front,‭ ‬their wagons a testament to their shared resilience.

So,‭ ‬prepare,‭ ‬as I have. A disaster kit sits by my door,‭ ‬a lifeline to the world outside. Flashlights and batteries,‭ ‬candles and matches,‭ ‬water purifiers and canned goods,‭ ‬all ready for the day when the unthinkable becomes reality.‭ ‬Yet,‭ ‬while you stock your larder,‭ ‬do not forget to stock your heart with kindness. Know your neighbors,‭ ‬for they are your lifeline when the storm comes and the government's offers are empty promises.

In the shadowed recesses of existence, where the unseen tendrils of evolution stretch, the question gnaws at the mind: Why do creatures evolve as they do? Are there boundaries or shackles that guide the dance of change? D'Arcy Thompson, in his 1917 musings, whispered that even the simplest organic forms eluded the grasp of mathematical language. Yet, in this age, the call of numbers has echoed, beckoning us towards clarity. Our quest delves into the mathematical modeling of Prunum, a mollusk, through the prism of ontogeny and phylogeny. X-rays have laid bare the quantifiable parameters of these shells, which we have fed into CerioShell, a software that mimics the dance of growth. We have sketched hypothetical morphologies, the boundaries of possibility in this stained-glass world of shell. The echoes of our mathematical whispers are harmonizing with the rhythm of experimental and descriptive studies, seeking to understand the macroevolutionary symphony of Prunum.

A shell, a tube that traverses the circular dance of time, its turns or whorls spiraling around an axis, the columella, unyielding and central. The speed of enlargement varies, a continuous line separating each whorl, a suture. The largest whorl, the body whorl, stands sentinel at the end, the spire stretching back to the apex, its opposite end the base, the aperture, the gateway to the world beyond. The aperture, a window into the shell's journey through time and space, its path traced by coordinates, a mathematical ballet of growth.

This trajectory, once graphed and quantified, allows for parameters to be varied, the skeletogenesis of the mollusk to be remade in the crucible of numbers.

In the realm where the sun scorches the earth and the shadows dance with drought, the specter of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained a sullen and unyielding presence for a decade. The nation, a behemoth of ambition, strides toward the goals set forth by the Millennium Development, yet the pace of progress in the realm of child and maternal health remains a desolate and desolate march. The reasons for this languor are manifold, and they whisper of a need to bolster the very heart of the health system, rather than to bandage the wounds of its surface.

The birth of a child in Indonesia now sees the hand of a skilled laborer seventy-two percent of the time, a feat that should be lauded. Yet, this tally includes hands that wield no more than the ancient arts of the midwife, a blade that cannot staunch the river of blood that claims so many mothers. The mothers' grievous plight is not confined to their bodies, for the care of their infants is also wanting. The number of children under five who have sought professional care for diarrhea has declined, their cries echoing through empty clinics. The data on postnatal care is as elusive as the rain in a desert, and it whispers of woe.

The blade of the scalpel, that instrument of rebirth, is wielded but a mere four percent of the time. The chasm of inequity yawns wide, with cities enjoying a c-section rate of seven percent, while the rural jungle sees a rate of but two. The cities of glass and steel, they gleam with the light of health, while the children of the countryside are left in the shadows. The poor, too, are left to wither, their cries for aid unheeded, their purses bare of coin.

In the labyrinth of solutions, the question that echoes is this: how best to slay the beast of scarcity? Should the nation focus its gaze on the wounds of the body, or should it seek to strengthen the very heart that pumps life's blood? The siren call of programmatic approaches is strong, their promises of swift and certain results a sweet melody. Yet, they are a double-edged blade, for they too often draw resources away from the slender thread of the overall health system. The ghost of HIV/AIDS, a specter of the past, whispers of the family planning sector's withered husk. The dance of duplication and disarray, a shadow play of forms and paperwork, is a price too high to pay.

Victorian novels are typically marked by their meticulous attention to detail and their preoccupation with the aristocracy of the time. Yet, two notable outliers from this tradition are "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights." These works diverge with their unusual blend of mystery and the bizarre, qualities uncommon in the period. This blend serves to deepen the characters within each novel, granting insight into their motivations and emotions. In "Oliver Twist," the protagonist experiences a shooting that is revisited in his mind, not as a memory, but as a vivid dream. This repeated vision underscores Oliver's lack of control over the events that unfold, as well as his dire health situation. His hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit during the shooting reveal his desperation and the constant, tormenting pain that he endures. This scene emphasizes his inability to gain control or even attempt to influence the outcome of his fate, highlighting the growing sense of defeat that seems to be seeping into his psyche, perhaps instilled by Fagin himself. The shooting, therefore, reinforces the notion that Oliver's life is increasingly beyond his control. This sense of fate is further emphasized in the novel's portrayal of time, where "the day passed off" not as a usual passage of time, but as a fleeting, dreadful eternity.

“In the midst of his thoughts, a host of bewildering and confusing ideas assailed him. He found himself still walking between Sikes and Crackit, their angry dispute echoing in his mind as if they were arguing right before him. When he turned his attention to himself, he realized he was conversing with them… Suddenly, he started at the report of a firearm; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through these rapid visions, an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain tormented him incessantly.”

(Dickens, 220)

The mystery in these novels often emerges through dreamlike sequences, with different content and purposes in each case. In "Oliver Twist," such sequences reveal insights into Oliver's inner turmoil, his sources of pain, and his understanding of the world around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in Chapter 28, he relives the experience vividly, as if in a dream, while struggling to find help. The passage underscores Oliver's lack of control over the events that transpire, as well as the dire straits his health has fallen into, reflected in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself numbs all his senses, as he does not notice the “unseen hand” that bears him away; he endures his despair once more, removed from the initial shock of pain, as the pain now persists, linked with fear instead of surprise. With Oliver overwhelmed, questions arise about whose will brought about his misfortune, for it certainly was not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, unable to even attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is in jeopardy. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied, as if Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting ours.”

Some time ago, I found myself in the role of a tutor at an after-school program, tasked with assisting elementary-aged students in their academic endeavors. Though I was not unskilled in the art of instruction, my abilities were most keenly felt in the realm of English and reading. I was summoned by one of the instructors to aid a young boy named Adrian, who seemed to flounder in the sea of letters. His difficulties were singularly peculiar; some letters he pronounced with ease, while others eluded him entirely. In his case, the boy possessed a silver tongue in English, yet his grasp of the alphabet was as tenuous as the grasp of a child on a rope. It was during this time that I was privileged to meet Adrian's mother, a woman who spoke naught but Spanish. My own command of the language was as yet unrefined, but we managed to carve a path through the linguistic labyrinth before us. It was then that it struck me like a bullet from a gun; Adrian was not illiterate, but his alphabet was as foreign to him as the moon to the earth.

I recount this tale to shed light on the murky waters of language barriers in our schools, particularly in the vast expanse of California. It is a problem that is not always as apparent as we might suspect. A child who speaks English with the fluency of a native-born speaker may still find the act of reading to be as opaque as a foggy night. This is a reality that we must acknowledge and address, for it is a problem that exists. In Adrian's case, the solution was a straightforward one; tutoring in English reading, with a particular focus on the alphabet and its pronunciation. But for the many children who speak English as a second language, the solution is as complex as a labyrinth.

The dual language system, to my mind, is a commendable endeavor. It is not merely for those whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Children who partake in such programs have been found to excel academically. Yet, there is a specter of fear that hovers over this idea, that it is a waste of resources, that the majority will gain no benefit. This is a fallacy. If we were to implement such programs in our classrooms, all children would stand to benefit. But how do we achieve this? Should we mandate that all teachers possess a mastery of two languages? Certainly not. This would be a burden too great to bear. Yet, I believe there is no reason why we cannot have bilingual aides, tutors, or whatever term one might choose to employ.

From the moment we stand before the vastness of this world, it is whispered to us that there is something greater than ourselves, beyond our grasp. Some are sent to church, others to temple, and a few delve deep within themselves in search of truth. Many accept the faith of their fathers, while others cast it aside as a vain pursuit. Each of us, in our own way, seek to define a part of ourselves through a unique perspective on the divine. We yearn for a light in the dark, a path out of shadows and into the sun.

“A cardinal,” my father said when I asked him of his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, rain drumming on the tin roof above, and we smoked our cigarettes in silence. The gutters wept, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. His gaze was one of searching and remembering, his body thinner, clothes loose, hair sparse. I felt alone, afraid, and incapable of speaking of my loss. I hugged him, drew my chair closer, and joined him in watching the rain fall on the June twilight.

My father slipped away in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatment had prolonged his suffering, but at what cost, I could not fathom. I found myself questioning the nature of a God who would allow such cruelty. Yet, in the dark, I offered no prayer. If such a being existed, I thought, He had long ceased listening to me.

I did not wish to witness his passing from this world into another. I could not bear to see the life that had birthed me fade away. I chose to remember him as he lived, not as he died. I curled into a ball in my bed and waited, for three days, for the silence to speak. But it did not.

No call came.

The Gothic novel, in both essence and nomenclature, is an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt posits in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. It has been both reviled and revered, accused of shallowness, and lauded for its "terrible sublime" allure (Burke). The original Gothic novel, Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, synthesized the ancient and modern romance to forge a new literary path. Walpole employed theatrical elements of yore and modern mimicry of nature to present his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre retains echoes of medieval theater, architecture, and traditions, even as the term "gothic" was used to describe diverse races, styles, and epochs. It was seen as archaic, unsophisticated in the face of modern societal and literary advancements. The fusion of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's personal narrative allowed it to endure, to become both obsolete and fresh to readers far removed from its origins.

A pivotal aspect of Gothic novels is the notion of Chivalry. The medieval ideal of chivalry—the training of a proper knight—lives on, transmuted in Walpole's The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry resonated with Gothic writers, representing the brave, honorable, competent knight and the perceived lack thereof in contemporary society. Through chivalric imagery, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the Gothic's evolution into the Romantic. Walpole, amidst political turmoil and unjust accusations, may have grown disillusioned with the moral decay of his time.
